Morals&rdquo;, <em>Philosophy and Phenomenological Research</em>,
62(1): 1&ndash;32. doi:10.2307/2653587</li>

<li>Stevenson, Charles Leslie, 1938, &ldquo;Persuasive
Definitions&rdquo;, <em>Mind</em>, 47(187): 331&ndash;50.</li>

<li>Stojanovic, Isidora, 2016, &ldquo;Expressing Aesthetic Judgments
in Context&rdquo;, <em>Inquiry</em>, 59(6): 663&ndash;85.
doi:10.1080/0020174X.2016.1208922</li>

<li>Sundell, Timothy, 2016, &ldquo;The Tasty, the Bold, and the
Beautiful&rdquo;, <em>Inquiry</em>, 59(6): 793&ndash;818.
doi:10.1080/0020174X.2016.1208918</li>

<li>Tappolet, Christine, 2004, &ldquo;Through Thick and Thin: Good and
its Determinates&rdquo;, <em>Dialectica</em>, 58(2): 207&ndash;21.
doi:10.1111/j.1746-8361.2004.tb00297.x</li>

<li>V&auml;yrynen, Pekka, 2008, &ldquo;Slim Epistemology with a Thick
Skin&rdquo;, in Kotzee and Wanderer 2008: 389&ndash;412.
doi:10.1080/05568640809485228</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2011, &ldquo;Thick Concepts and
Variability&rdquo;, <em>Philosophers&rsquo; Imprint</em>, 11(1)
January,
 <a href="http://hdl.handle.net/2027/spo.3521354.0011.001" target="other">available online</a>.</li>
 
<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2012, &ldquo;Thick Concepts: Where&rsquo;s
Evaluation?&rdquo;, <em>Oxford Studies in Metaethics</em>, Russ
Shafer-Landau (ed.), 7: 235&ndash;70.
doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780199653492.003.0008</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2013, <em>The Lewd, the Rude and the
Nasty</em>, New York: Oxford University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2014, &ldquo;Shapelessness in
Context&rdquo;, <em>No&ucirc;s</em>, 48(3): 573&ndash;93.
doi:10.1111/j.1468-0068.2012.00877.x</li>

<li>Willemsen, Pascale and Kevin Reuter, 2021, &ldquo;Separating the
Evaluative from the Descriptive: An Empirical Study of Thick
Concepts&rdquo;, <em>Thought</em>, 10:
135&ndash;46. doi:10.1002/tht3.488</li>

<li>Williams, Bernard, 1981, &ldquo;Internal and External
Reasons&rdquo;, in his <em>Moral Luck</em>, Cambridge: Cambridge
University Press, pp. 101&ndash;13.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1985, <em>Ethics and the Limits of
Philosophy</em>, Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press.</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 1995, &ldquo;Truth in Ethics&rdquo;,
<em>Ratio</em>, 8(3): 227&ndash;42.
doi:10.1111/j.1467-9329.1995.tb00085.x</li>

<li>Williamson, Timothy, 2009, &ldquo;Reference, Inference, and the
Semantics of Pejoratives&rdquo;, in Joseph Almog and Paolo Leonardi
(eds.), <em>The Philosophy of David Kaplan</em>, Oxford: Oxford
University Press, pp. 137&ndash;58.
doi:10.1093/acprof:oso/9780195367881.003.0009</li>

<li>Yaffe, Gideon, 2000, &ldquo;Free Will and Agency at Its
Best&rdquo;, <em>Philosophical Perspectives</em>, 14: 203&ndash;229.
doi:10.1111/0029-4624.34.s14.11</li>

<li>Zakkou, Julia, 2003, &ldquo;Conventional Evaluativity&rdquo;,
<em>Australasian Journal of Philosophy</em>, 101(2): 440&ndash;54.
doi:10.1080/00048402.2021.2013264</li>

<li>Zangwill, Nick, 1995, &ldquo;The Beautiful, the Dainty and the
Dumpy&rdquo;, <em>British Journal of Aesthetics</em>, 35(4):
317&ndash;29. doi:10.1093/bjaesthetics/35.4.317</li>

<li>&ndash;&ndash;&ndash;, 2013, &ldquo;Moral Metaphor and Thick
Concepts: What Moral Philosophy Can Learn from Aesthetics&rdquo;, in
